### 3. NETCONF and RESTCONF Private Candidate Datastores
* **Presenter:** James Cumming
* **Slides:** [02-NETCONF and RESTCONF Private Candidates](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-netconf-netconf-and-restconf-private-candidates-00)
* **Draft:** [draft-ietf-netconf-privcand](https://datatracker.ietf.org/id/draft-ietf-netconf-privcand)
* **Discussion:**
  * **Coexistence with Shared Candidates:** The draft assumes private and shared candidates can coexist across different sessions but not within the same session. Shared candidate remains a prerequisite due to feature constraints in YANG 1.0. Rob Wilton agreed this is a pragmatic solution.
  * **Metadata for In-Conflict Marker:** Qin Wu agreed that specifying metadata timestamps is out of scope. Rob Wilton suggested defining the metadata annotation without requiring its mandatory use to avoid under-specifying error paths.
  * **Conflict Resolution:** Rob Wilton noted that in "auto-update" mode, a commit operation should logically behave as a no-op since state is already updated. James Cumming agreed to clarify this.
  * **Delete Config:** The authors will remove reference to the `delete-config` RPC as it was a legacy element from when private candidates were defined as a distinct datastore.

