### 6. List Pagination for YANG-driven Protocols
* **Presenter:** Qin Wu
* **Slides:** [05-List Pagination for YANG-driven Protocols](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-netconf-list-pagination-for-yang-driven-protocols-03)
* **Drafts:** 
  * [draft-ietf-netconf-list-pagination](https://datatracker.ietf.org/id/draft-ietf-netconf-list-pagination)
  * [draft-ietf-netconf-list-pagination-nc](https://datatracker.ietf.org/id/draft-ietf-netconf-list-pagination-nc)
  * [draft-ietf-netconf-list-pagination-rc](https://datatracker.ietf.org/id/draft-ietf-netconf-list-pagination-rc)
* **Discussion:**
  * Qin Wu presented updates across all three pagination drafts. Key changes include moving consolidated error information to the base draft and replacing query parameters with RPC inputs in the NETCONF extension.
  * **Cursor Page Size (Issue 2):** The group discussed whether cursors should encode/embed page limits or remain context-free. Rob Wilton supported keeping the cursor context-free (client sends the limit each time) to prevent the server from needing to maintain complex session states.
  * **Offset vs. Cursor Support (Issue 3):** Kent Watsen argued that clients should be mandated to support both options to give servers the flexibility to implement high-performance cursors. Per Hedeland preferred making offset mandatory on the server due to its simplicity. Rob Wilton noted that offsets are highly inefficient for certain non-SQL databases, whereas cursors map much better to their internal indexing. No consensus was reached, and the discussion will continue on the list.

