### 8. YANG Push v2 Update
* **Presenter:** Rob Wilton
* **Slides:** [07-YANG Push v2 Update](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-netconf-07-yang-push-v2-update-00)
* **Draft:** [draft-ietf-netconf-yang-push-2](https://datatracker.ietf.org/id/draft-ietf-netconf-yang-push-2)
* **Discussion:**
  * **YANG Path (yPath):** James Cumming is breaking out yPath into a separate document so that it can be generically utilized by other efforts (e.g., YANG Packages, NETCONF, and RESTCONF) without duplicating work.
  * **Merge/Replace Semantics:** The authors agreed to simplify on-change notifications by removing the "replace" operation, relying entirely on "merge" semantics. Balazs Lengyel asked how item deletions are handled in lists. Rob Wilton clarified that deletions will be sent as distinct delete messages, which aligns better with message brokers.
  * **Envelope Consolidation:** As agreed at IETF 125, the notification envelope specification ([draft-ietf-netconf-notif-envelope](https://datatracker.ietf.org/id/draft-ietf-netconf-notif-envelope)) is being consolidated into this draft.
  * **On-Change Statistics:** The group discussed dampening. The consensus is that dampening statistics should be handled implicitly by the server to protect its control plane, rather than being configurable by the client.

